**Sorting in C++**

C++ provides several ways to sort data, including:

### 1. Using the `std::sort` Algorithm

The `std::sort` algorithm is a part of the C++ Standard Template Library (STL) and is the most commonly used sorting function in C++.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> numbers = {4, 2, 7, 1, 3};
    std::sort(numbers.begin(), numbers.end());

    for (const auto& num : numbers) {
        std::cout << num << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

### 2. Using the `std::stable_sort` Algorithm

The `std::stable_sort` algorithm is similar to `std::sort`, but it preserves the relative order of equal elements.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> numbers = {4, 2, 7, 1, 3};
    std::stable_sort(numbers.begin(), numbers.end());

    for (const auto& num : numbers) {
        std::cout << num << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

### 3. Implementing a Custom Sorting Algorithm

If you want to implement a custom sorting algorithm, you can use a simple sorting algorithm like Bubble Sort or a more complex algorithm like Quick Sort.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                arr[j + 1] = temp;
            }
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    int numbers[] = {4, 2, 7, 1, 3};
    int n = sizeof(numbers) / sizeof(numbers[0]);
    bubbleSort(numbers, n);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        std::cout << numbers[i] << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

### Choosing a Sorting Algorithm

When choosing a sorting algorithm, consider the following factors:

* **Time complexity**: The time complexity of the algorithm, which determines how long it takes to sort the data.
* **Space complexity**: The space complexity of the algorithm, which determines how much memory it uses.
* **Stability**: Whether the algorithm preserves the relative order of equal elements.
* **Efficiency**: The efficiency of the algorithm, which determines how well it performs on large datasets.

In general, `std::sort` is the recommended sorting algorithm in C++ because it is efficient, stable, and easy to use. However, if you need to implement a custom sorting algorithm, consider using a well-known algorithm like Quick Sort or Merge Sort.

**Sorting in C++**

C++ provides several sorting algorithms, including `std::sort`, `std::stable_sort`, and `std::partial_sort`. Here, we'll focus on `std::sort`, which is the most commonly used.

### Using `std::sort`

`std::sort` is a part of the C++ Standard Template Library (STL) and is defined in the `<algorithm>` header. It sorts the elements in the range `[first, last)` in ascending order.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int arr[] = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9};
    int n = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);

    // Sort the array
    std::sort(arr, arr + n);

    // Print the sorted array
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        std::cout << arr[i] << " ";
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

### Custom Sorting

If you need to sort custom objects, you can provide a custom comparison function or operator.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>

struct Person {
    std::string name;
    int age;
};

// Custom comparison function
bool compareByAge(const Person& a, const Person& b) {
    return a.age < b.age;
}

int main() {
    Person people[] = {{"John", 25}, {"Alice", 30}, {"Bob", 20}};
    int n = sizeof(people) / sizeof(people[0]);

    // Sort by age
    std::sort(people, people + n, compareByAge);

    // Print the sorted array
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        std::cout << people[i].name << " (" << people[i].age << ")" << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Sorting with Lambda Functions

You can also use lambda functions for custom sorting.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>

struct Person {
    std::string name;
    int age;
};

int main() {
    Person people[] = {{"John", 25}, {"Alice", 30}, {"Bob", 20}};
    int n = sizeof(people) / sizeof(people[0]);

    // Sort by age using a lambda function
    std::sort(people, people + n, [](const Person& a, const Person& b) {
        return a.age < b.age;
    });

    // Print the sorted array
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        std::cout << people[i].name << " (" << people[i].age << ")" << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Time Complexity

The time complexity of `std::sort` is O(n log n) on average, making it suitable for large datasets. However, the actual performance may vary depending on the specific use case and data distribution.
